%N A386600 a(n) is the number of primes q < p = prime(n) such that p - q is a perfect square.
%C A386600 If prime(n) - 2 is a perfect square, then exactly one odd perfect square is included in the count. Otherwise, every perfect square counted is even.
%H A386600 Felix Huber, <a href="/A386600/b386600.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A386600 a(A000720(A065377(n))) = 0.
%F A386600 a(A000720(A065376(n))) > 0.
%F A386600 Trivial upper bound: a(n) < A000720(n).
%e A386600 a(5) = 2 because prime(5) = 11 and 11 - 2 = 3^2 and 11 - 7 = 2^2 are perfect squares. 11 - 3 = 8 and 11 - 5 = 6 are not perfect squares.
%p A386600 A386600:=proc(n)
%p A386600     local a,i,p;
%p A386600     a:=0;
%p A386600     for i to n-1 do
%p A386600         p:=ithprime(n);
%p A386600         if issqr(p-ithprime(i)) then
%p A386600             a:=a+1
%p A386600         fi
%p A386600     od;
%p A386600     return a
%p A386600 end proc;
%p A386600 seq(A386600(n),n=1..88);
%t A386600 a[n_]:=Total[Boole[IntegerQ/@Surd[Prime[n]-Prime[Range[n-1]],2]]];Array[a,88] (* _James C. McMahon_, Oct 31 2025 *)
%o A386600 (PARI) a(n) = my(vp=primes(n)); sum(k=1, n-1, issquare(vp[n] - vp[k])); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Oct 27 2025
